bib.title: Proton elastic scattering cross-section on boron from 0.5 to 3.3 MeV

free_txt: Last checking has been done.
Measured cross section of (P,P) scattering on natural
boron at 170 degree.
- By authors. Unfortunately, the data published in
tabular form in the paper for the 170 scattering angle
have a bias.  The data for 170 degree included below
are anyway the right.
Fifteen Si detectors were placed at backward angles
from 100 to 170 degrees in step 5 degrees; they were
cooled at liquid nitrogen.
Estimated uncertainty of aperture area and
distance of each collimator from the beam spot.
Uncertainty of target thickness.
Uncertainty of integrated current.
Upper limit of statistical error
Conservative estimate of total error of
absolute cross section
The uncertainty on the proton beam energy
Proton beam currents were in the range 100-200
nanoampere.
Self-supporting foils of approximately 20 mugramm/
cm**2 natural boron were used as target.
The proton energy loss in the target ranged from about
7 to 2 KeV.
From M.Chiari
By M.Chiari 29-dec-2001
However, some discrepancies occur: in particular,
data on P+B-10 scattering at 150 degrees are about 15%
lower than the ones from Rel-Ref.
The cross section
values from that work are about 1.5-2 times those
reported here and those from other authors.
In general, our cross section curves agree well in
shape with the other data, and the absolute values are
in good agreement wiyh those from Symons+ and from
Segel+. However, some dicrepancies occur: data at 155
degrees are about 15% higher than those from Tautfest+
and data at 165 degrees are about 18% higher than the
ones from Mayer+. It should be noted that these
discrepancies are essentially systematic, even though
there is not well-defined trend. - All the comments by
authors.
